        "content": "<p>The following is an example of a recursively defined function:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">--- &lt; --- (i)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"bp\">|</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">2</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">1</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">+</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"c1\">--- &lt; --- (ii)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Question: What are the correct names for each \"branch\" of the function?</p>\n<p>For an induction proof, we have a <strong>base case</strong>, and an <strong>inductive step</strong>. But those don't apply to a definition.</p>\n<p>Given the LaTeX name for such definition is \"cases\", my guess would be: </p>\n<ul>\n<li>(i) is a base case, or a <strong>ground case</strong>.</li>\n<li>(ii) is the <strong>recursive case</strong>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I've seen the word <strong>branch</strong> used, but this feels very much from the world of programming and <strong>implementation</strong> rather than the <strong>semantics</strong> of a recursively defined function.</p>",
        "id": 491886146,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1736005226
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Syntactically the <code>| _ =&gt; _</code> syntax is known as a \"match arm\"</p>",
        "id": 491887918,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1736006828
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Thanks Eric,</p>\n<p>Do you know what they're called in \"pure maths\", as in, outside the world of Lean?</p>",
        "id": 491890625,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1736009463
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>In the real world we just say \"define f recursively by f(0)=0 and f(n+1)=...\".</p>",
        "id": 491890887,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Buzzard",
        "timestamp": 1736009731
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The equation <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mi>f</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">f(n + 1) = 2n + 1 + f(n)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">2</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7278em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">+</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10764em;\">f</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is called a \"recurrence relation\".</p>",
